Dear Jobst,

Werehatrack stated that he was younger and lighter and riding around
in his junior-high school's faculty parking lot.

Parking lots are often flat, badly oil-stained, and much slipperier
after a downpour than steep California side-streets--not much water
stays on a ~30% grade.

The parking lot was certainly much flatter than Filbert, so
Werehatrack could lean forward much more effectively than you could
lean on a steep hill, thus putting less weight on his rear tire.

You've often mentioned how you have to lean forward just to keep the
front wheel from coming up on steep climbs, haven't you? Obviously
you're nowhere near as far of true forward on your climbs as the kid
sliding around in the video.

In junior high, Werehatrack was probably considerably lighter than
your ~180 pounds, putting even less weight on his rear tire.

So I believe him quite easily.

Incidentally, if someone had written the same sort of skeptical reply
to one of your posts, wouldn't you be demanding to know whether they
were calling you a liar?

Cheers,

Carl Fogel
