Dear Dave,

Several posters have suggested water, which might work. Ice or frost
are also faint possibilities.

But I can't make out any stains on the back of his white robe.

Of course, the video quality is too low to make out details.

But still I'd expect to see a mess on the white robe if water (or ice
or frost) were being spun up in all those frantic sliding, low-speed,
wheel-spinning circles.

I do see something white thrown up by the rear tire. And I see whitish
streaks on the road. But it doesn't seem to carry around, as water,
ice, or frost would be carried by a wet tire.

So I'm leaning toward bleach or some other stuff that can be easily
added and easily practiced on.

The trouble with ice or frost is that it's likely to be so rare that
practice time would be severely limited. And I expect that it would
leave a mess.

A water-covered road is much easier to find for practice, but the
water ought to leave a large, dirty stain on the white robe.

Bleach (or something like it) on a rear tire (or on the pavement)
might produce the white "smoke" and the white smears, and it would be
easy to use for practice.

(Fine sand has been suggested, which might puff up like the white
"smoke," but I can't see how the sand would leave the white smears on
the road.)

Maybe that wild cartoon-like trick is easier than it seems, but that
fellow looks as if he practiced his stunt until he was ready to take
it on the road in front of a camera. He only puts his foot down once,
at the very end.

It's a bit like magic tricks. I always guess wrong when I try to
figure them out--which never surprises magicians. It won't startle me
if we eventually learn that the stunt involves neither frost, ice,
water, bleach, sand, or any other suggestion made so far.

Cheers,

Carl Fogel
